prompt:
### Instruction: Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
3x + 5 &\text{if }x<-3, \\
7-4x&\text{if }x\ge -3.
\end{cases}

Let’s think step by step.

To find \( f(-10) \) using the piecewise function, we need to determine which part of the function to use based on the value of \( x = -10 \).
The function is defined as:
\[
f(x) =
\begin{cases}
3x + 5 & \text{if } x < -3, \\
7 - 4x & \text{if } x \ge -3.
\end{cases}
\]
Since \(-10 < -3\), we use the first part of the function:
\[
f(x) = 3x + 5.
\]
Now substitute \( x = -10 \) into this expression:
\[
f(-10) = 3(-10) + 5.
\]
Calculate:
\[
f(-10) = -30 + 5 = -25.
\]
Therefore, \( f(-10) = -25 \).
